To achieve this functionality, you can implement it in various programming languages. Below are examples in Python and JavaScript, showing how to create a list (or array in JavaScript) that maintains a maximum of 10 elements. When a new element is appended, and the list already has 10 elements, the first element is removed before appending the new one.

### Python Example

```python
class LimitedList:
    def __init__(self, limit=10):
        self.limit = limit
        self.items = []

    def append(self, item):
        if len(self.items) >= self.limit:
            self.items.pop(0)  # Remove the first element
        self.items.append(item)

    def __str__(self):
        return str(self.items)

# Example usage
my_list = LimitedList(10)
for i in range(15):
    my_list.append(i)
    print(my_list)  # This will show the last 10 elements added
```

### JavaScript Example

```javascript
class LimitedArray {
    constructor(limit = 10) {
        this.limit = limit;
        this.items = [];
    }

    append(item) {
        if (this.items.length >= this.limit) {
            this.items.shift(); // Remove the first element
        }
        this.items.push(item);
    }

    print() {
        console.log(this.items);
    }
}

// Example usage
const myList = new LimitedArray(10);
for (let i = 0; i < 15; i++) {
    myList.append(i);
    myList.print(); // This will show the last 10 elements added
}
```

These examples define a class (`LimitedList` in Python and `LimitedArray` in JavaScript) that encapsulates the functionality of maintaining a maximum of 10 elements. When appending a new element, if the list/array has reached its limit, the first element is removed before the new one is added. This way, the size of the list/array is kept within the specified limit.
